<font color="#FF0000">RULES OF ENGAGEMENT IN WAR?</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jun 30 11:23:19 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Professor Gerald :<br>
 <br>
Were the Rules of engagement different for the Marines then for the Army? I don't know.  I only know that we were constantly called upon to rescue the Green Berets at Thuong Duc because they kept waiting for the enemy to get into the wire before opening up.<br><br>
I also recall being called into the colonel's office and standing at attention alongside my platoon lieutenant while the colonel lectured me about rules of engagement. In the colonels office was a village chief, two other local officials a Korean interpreter, a major, my captain who I believe at that time happened to be Captain Charles Robb (Johnson's son in Law), and a women whose legs I had shot off. The Colonel was demanding an explanation not from my Captain nor the Lieutenant but from me as I had done the shooting.<br><br>
We had been patrolling in Dodge City in an area where all so-called friendies had been evacuated. It was suppose to be a free fire zone. My gun team was behind 1st squad when we came upon a clearing. Off in the distance three individuals were out in the open rice paddies observing the patrol. As soon as they noticed we had seen them, they took off running. The 1st squad team leader yelled for them to stop, but they kept running. Others in the squad yelled for them to stop, and they ran faster. While the squad leader and fire team leaders gathered to engage in a conversation about the rules of engagement, I drop the gun off my shoulder and opened fire. All three went down, got up and ran off into the jungle. My platoon lieutenant was angry because we would now have to go search for the bodies. We did and found blood splattered and going off in different directions. We found other evidence that they enemy had been in that area but no bodies. <br><br>
Later that evening when we arrived at the base of Hill 55, I was summons to the colonel's office. The village chief and the women wanted compensation from the Marine Corps for my having shot the poor farming women. When given the opportunity, I asked the colonel about the other two we had shot and he seemed puzzled, What they had failed to mention was the other two younger men who had been with her out in the field. Individuals, who never came forward, appeared or had been mentioned. Were they NVA?<br>
An argument ensued between the Korean interpreter and the village chief until he booted them out of the barracks threatening to shoot the women himself because he had determined that she was in fact involved with the two NVA soldiers. They had been gathering information about our patrol.  <br><br>
Interesting in February of this year I obtained a copy of the final report about that incident and found out that the Marine Corps later did compensate the women with $2000.00 for her injuries. RULES OF ENGAGEMENT? Its called WAR for a reason. The Geneva card we carried you know as well I do, was a joke. Present it to the NVA soldiers if you are captured we were told and they would abide by its declaration. Of course they would first shove it into your private parts while they mutilated you piece by piece. Why are so many American fighting men still missing?<br>
 <br>
I dealt with many perimeter officers that did not understand the war we fought in the field, who tried to tell us not to lock and load until we saw the whites of their eyes. Who asked, are you sure you are getting incoming? Are they green tracers or red tracers being shot at you? Wait until we get the Ok, from our intelligence officers. If we waited for them to get to the wire as you have suggested we usually would have had to hand the radio mike to the enemy so that the poogues or intelligent officers in the rear could talk to them and thereby confirm they were indeed the enemy before giving us the OK to open fire. Was this one of the reason others that came after us begin to use drugs and felt our country had betrayed them? <br>
You cannot fight a war when only one side followed Rules of Engagement. The difference between the US fighting men and the enemy was that, YES we regretted that innocent people were victims of our engagements, I regretted that the women was shot, do I regret shooting her and the others? NO. Its called WAR and there will always be innocent victims that will suffer, it's been that way for the ages and in the ultimate battle we all know the populated cities are primary targets. But, don't we have rules of engagements in place for that?  I hope for your sake they honor them. <br>
After July 1968, the war as we knew it changed. Public opinion influenced by the liberal media back home begin to dictate how the war in Nam was suppose to be fought and because of that we lost many many Us soldiers. We fought the communist in the rice paddy fields of Southeast Asia and beat them in every battle but could not defeat the Jane Fonda's type communist sympathizers back home, that never saw what the NVA did to innocent civilians.  What is interesting is that the greatest blow we inflicted upon the communist forces in South Vietnam was during the 68 Tet offensive. That engagement eliminated almost all so called VC soldiers still fighting in the South, that occurred before you arrived, yet it was displayed as a lost back home.<br>
 I'm Cook Barela and those are my thoughts!<br><br>

